### Introduction

::: .row

::: .col-12 .col-md-8
Microorganisms—tiny living entities such as bacteria, fungi, protozoa, and microscopic algae—are often invisible to the naked eye, yet they play an essential role in maintaining ecological balance. In the food chain, microorganisms are fundamental contributors at multiple levels, from primary production to decomposition. They influence nutrient cycling, energy transfer, and the survival of various life forms, making them indispensable for both natural ecosystems and human-managed environments like agriculture and aquaculture.
